segments.text: cable company and so we wrapped around and stretched them and it would have been pretty difficult for it to move.

I mean they would, the tradition back then was, you know, if it's still standing when the sun comes up, you know, we'll probably win the game or something because those things were so bound together that it was pretty hard for them to move.
Was anybody, do you remember any injuries during your four years?
Oh yeah, we had guys that were injured but not
What kind of injuries?
I don't know if anything serious.
I mean, there's guys that would not move their hands around and get caught as they were loading something on the truck and I'm sure there were some broken bones and a few things like that.
I remember we had one kid, when I was a sophomore, there was a kid that lived, this is unbelievable, I mean, we lived on the third floor and there was a fish next to us and he was
He always seemed kind of depressed, just about everything.
And all of a sudden, one day, his old lady comes in and says, Mr. Sharp, Fish Cardinal, I think was his name.
Probably ought not to use his name, but he just tried to commit suicide.
And this kid had jumped face first out of the dorm window onto the ground.
And I looked down there, and there was this kid spread out on the ground.
And fortunately, it had rained a lot the day before, and he hit it, and it kind of was mud, and we revived him, and then he left school right after that.
That was the kind of thing.
And at that point with Bonfire, did any of y'all worry about the possibility of a serious, serious accident?
No.
I don't ever remember even thinking about it.
as you think back about Bonfire, what importance, what does Bonfire's importance value to A&M?
Well, you know, I told you before about how those Walton Hall and some of those folks got by.
I mean, I will guarantee you that a whole bunch of former students of A&M would take a look at
some of their best friends right now 20 years or 30 years later, if you think about it, go back and there are people they work right next to in building that.
For the core, the bonfire, a lot of part of the bonfire was putting to the test all those leadership skills that you've been learning for four or five years.
I mean it was the first practical way you had to
do this?
Is somebody going to take orders?
Are they going to be disciplined enough to do exactly what you say?
Stay away from the chainsaws and don't move the truck till we tell you and all this kind of stuff.
Can you take orders and can you follow orders?
And I think that was probably a big reason that we never got, we always got people hurt, I'm sure, but I don't remember any catastrophic deal.
And how long during your years, how long did an individual work on Bonfire?
Oh, some.
A month?
Some for a month, you know, go to class sometimes and go work on it.
But all of us would work on it for, you know, a couple weeks.
But somebody was out there in October, you know, cutting trees down and getting them ready.
See, I think this last year or two, I think it started Labor Day.
Yeah.
It had gotten bigger, bigger, bigger.
Yeah, they didn't talk about it much, but they were all out there doing that stuff.
I mean, right now, the kids are coming to guys like me
and gathered up money for the next year's bonfire to pay for equipment and stuff.
It's been the better part of a year working on it one form or another.
Let's see.
Bonfire, silver taps, midnight ale practice.
How much did your senior ring cost?
About $90.
The rumor back then was, everybody couldn't believe how cheap they were, and the rumor then was
that the Association of Farmer Students pays half of it.
If you go to my vintage at A&M and older, they still believe that the Association of Farmer Students paid half of that ring.
And it's never been true, best I can tell.
How did you feel about that ring when you first got it?
I remember exactly where I was in the Koch building when I put it on.
Picked it up, put it on.
I know one guy that got his 95 hours and quit school.
All he wanted was the ring.
He didn't give a damn about the diploma.
But I have an interesting ring story though.
I get my ring.
I go duck hunting and I've got this red Irish Setter that stubborn, won't go in the water.
It's cold and when it's cold your hands shrink.
This is a few years after I was graduated.
And I'm holding the dog with my left hand and I'm pointing to the duck in this 20 foot deep canal.
And I go like this, you know, swing my hand, go get it, and the ring flew off and went into this canal.
And it was about 30 degrees.
I took all my clothes off.
I beat the dog around the head and shoulders and dove in that stupid rice pond.
And the mud was, must have been 10 foot deep.
I never could find it.
It just liked to kill me.
Well, so I ordered another ring.
I put the ring on.
Da-da-da-da-da-da, I go down the road.
Years later, actually in 1998, I think it was, might have been 97, I had this Aggie named J.D.
Salinas who worked for me as a controller when I was a controller.
And he's flying from Laredo to Hidalgo County with me.
And we're in a little plane and he gets sick of his stomach.
And he throws up in my lap in the back of that plane.
And I said, Salinas, how long have you been working for me not counting today?
And I said, here's what you do.
You know, I said, he was sitting over here and I put my ring up above him on the ceiling of the plane.
I said, just stare at my ring and concentrate on it.
Count the stars.
Do anything you can.
Just concentrate on that ring and you won't be sick.
We're going to land here in about 10 minutes and just don't do this to me again.
After we landed,
He said, I got a question for you.
You older Aggies, y'all got different rings than we got, right?
And I said, no, it's the same ring.
Class of 91 has the same ring.
Class of 72 has and all this kind of stuff.
And he said, no, your ring's backward.
And I said, what are you talking about, my ring's backwards?
It's just like yours.
We took the ring off, and on all Aggie rings, the guns are over here, and the star is over here, except mine.
And I looked at that, and I looked at his ring.
There were two other Aggies that worked in that office.
I called them in.
I said, bring your rings in here.
We had a major emergency.
I looked at it, and my ring was totally reversed.
And so I called the ring clerk.
This was on a Friday afternoon.
I called the ring clerk, and I said, look, did something go on back when I was there that caused this to happen, all this kind of stuff?
And I explained it to her, and she said,
Jimmy, we got another one.
And she just hollered at the back and said, you know, we've had three of these or whatever it is, but all of them have been corrected.
So just bring yours in and we'll get it corrected.
And I was on my way down to get it corrected and I thought, no, wait a minute.
I'm going to keep it.
So I kept it.
And as best I know, this only Aggie ring like that is completely reversed.
The guns, my guns, as the ring faces out with the numbers, the guns are supposed to be
on the right side and the star is supposed to be on the left and mine is just the opposite of that.
But it's exactly the same... Everything else is exactly the same.
It's all the same stuff just a different... What happened was this crest probably goes on last and whoever did it reversed the crest.
I'm trying to think of all the events and or traditions that are important to A&M.
Final review.
Is that important?
Oh, yeah.
Describe what it meant to go through final review.
It was a real sad day for me.
I remember that day.
I remember that I was... First did your junior year.
Yeah, but my senior year is when it was real sad.
Junior year was a happy deal because, boy, all of a sudden you take your shoes off and you're walking on grass.
Boy, what a wonderful feeling.
No, the junior year was great because...
Well, I knew by that time that my senior year I was going to be on core staff and, you know, that it was going to be lots of fun.
And it was a little bit sad in the extent that I was leaving my outfit and going to another dormitory and stuff.
But junior year was lots of fun.
I mean, you just lived from the time that you do your first push-up.
You lived the time you put those boots on.
And so, you know, by then we'd already bought our boots.
Where did you get yours?
I actually bought mine from another senior, a guy named Richardson, in an outfit down below.
What did you pay for it?
Oh, I don't know.
I think maybe $150 or something.
Did you sell them or keep them?
I kept them.
I bronzed them.
You still have them?
I still have them.
I bronzed them and made lampshades out of them.
Why are eggy boots important?
They cost a lot, not in terms of dollars.
Hey, that's a good thought.
I like that.
I don't have anything that I spent more money on than that.
I mean more sweat equity on than those Aggie boots.
But I did agree.
I had a saber because I was on staff and saber harness and all that kind of stuff and I did agree

to sell them to a junior in my outfit and he'd agree that it was all brand new, the Sabre, I mean the Sabre holster, I wasn't going to sell the Sabre because I still have that right next to the boots but I agreed to sell everything else for two or three hundred dollars whatever it was and I remember I was so sad at the end of that that when that guy, that junior comes up and says hey give me your
spurs and give me your, you know, harness and all this kind of stuff and here's the money.
I told him to keep the money and give it, and I said you can keep that money if you promise to give this to somebody else next year.
So as far as I know they may still be on campus if somebody's honored that.
But it, that was, that was real sad.
May 6, 1972 was the day I graduated and it was...
Describe commencement.
Well, everybody came.
I mean, I don't know if they still come now, but there wasn't anybody that didn't show up at commencement.
When I got across the stage and Jack Williams handed me my diploma, I get off the stage and I'm out in the parking lot and I said, boy, I just got to take a look at it.
I opened it up and the tube was empty.
And so I called Lacey, Bob Lacey, who was Cooper's guy over there, and said, hey,
What is the deal with my diploma?
And he said, I had taken a correspondence course from UT and barely got it in in time.
And he didn't think I was going to get it in in time.
And so they didn't order one.
And so I got mine about two or three days later or something like that.
How big a crowd came from your family and friends?
Well, everybody.
Everybody.
I mean, any cousin I ever met, everybody was there.
My brother was making, fooling himself, screaming, knock him out, John, or whatever it was.
He was hollering and stuff like that.
No, G. Riley White was absolutely full, standing room only.
Is it important that every name is called, every hand?
Yeah.
Yeah, I think so.
But everybody walks across the state.
And I just thought of the name of that football announcer, C.K.
Weston.
CK what?
Esten.
Oh, CK Esten.
Yeah, that's right.
Good afternoon, football fans.
Welcome to Kyleville.
Because I think a year or so before you got here, what he would do is he would flip the mic off and then say something with some three- and four-letter words in it with the mic turned off.
One day, he said, that ought to take the son of a bitch's...
And Rutter summoned him to his office on Monday.
And he was scared to death.
And he went in and Rutter told him to come in and sit down.
And Rutter stared a hole through him as he was going through the chair in fear.
And then Rutter burst out laughing at him.
and then told him, look, you know darn good and well, now don't ever do that again.
It was funny.
I'll tell you the story I was going to tell you about Les Appel.
When I was a senior, the University of Texas had done away, or were doing away with their student government.
Remember when Bob Binder and all those people just abolished the student government?
And they had decided they wanted to rename the student senate.
Before they did that, they had voted to rename
Their mascot, the Armadillo, remember that?

Well, Saturday morning before a game, or maybe Sunday morning after a game, I was giving one of those speeches to the Association of Former Students, after one of the games, and Les Appelt, at the time, was president of the Association of Former Students.
I think they had just built maybe Appelt Hall, or maybe were fixing to, but anyway, he was president of the Association at the time.
And boy, I felt real bad.
It was a Sunday morning, and we'd
I'd probably been awake two hours before that.
And he comes up to me afterwards and he said, boy, you're in bad shape this morning, aren't you?
I said, yes, I sure am.
And he said, well, let's go out and get some breakfast somewhere.
I've got an idea I want to run by you.
And I said, what's that?
And he said, well, you know, UTU is thinking about doing away with these longhorn and putting in armadillos.
And I said, yeah, isn't that the stupidest thing you ever heard?
And he said, yes, and we need to capitalize on that.
And I said, what do you have in mind, Mr. Appleton?
He said, I want you to go out and print 5,000 or so bumper stickers.
Do you remember those?
Were you hearing one of those bumper stickers?
They were everywhere on campus.
And a little armadillo, orange armadillo digging, and it said, dig them dillos.
We printed 5,000 of them.
Les just loved them.
I sent it to Houston.
He said, oh, God, we've got to have more.
So he printed 20,000 more, 25,000 bumper stickers.
They were all over the bonfire.
They were all over on the helmets working on the bonfire and the whole bit.
And he called me about a week before the game.
He said, I want you to get some freshmen.
And I want one of those on every car in the parking lot at Kyle Field the day of the game.
He said, I don't care how many freshmen.
I'll pay for it.
Whatever's got to happen, you get that done.
I said, OK. Get it done.
He prints 10,000 more.
About four days before the game,
He drives down to college station and he said, he got me a new idea, Sharp.
And I said, what's that?
He said, I want you to go find some armadillo.
And I want these freshmen to get them.
I want about 20 or 30 of them.
And I want you to spray, remember this?
I want you to spray paint them, burn orange, and I want them released on the field while the UT band is in the middle of the field.
And I said, okay, may have to pay for this one.
These armadillos are hard to find.
He said, whatever.
Hang no expense.
I said, okay.
So I get two outfits of freshmen, buy them some, I'm sure it was Cokes or Dr. Pepper, to go out into the woods.
And they did.
They came up with 32 armadillos.
And we spray painted them.
burnt orange, and I'm sitting up in the stands of my date thinking, okay, let's see how this works out.
And here come these freshmen, four foot lockers full of armadillos, one from the east, one from the west, one from the north, one from the south.

Here's the UT band with big berth of block T formation the whole bit, and boom, they dump out these armadillos, and they herd them toward the band, and the armadillos run from four sides into the band.
I don't know if you remember this or not, but that band quit the field.
I mean, it disrupted halftime.
And I and one of yours and mine's favorite administrators came up into the stands and said, you've got real trouble here.
And I said, why are you talking to me, Dean?
He said, well, because the first, second, third, fourth, and fifth freshman that we caught immediately said, you the guy.
Was this Coldis?
Hannigan.
Oh, this is...
And I said, yeah, well, nothing bad going to happen, is it?
And he said, well, you could get kicked out of school for something like that.
And I said, oh, then we've got a real big problem.
And he said, what's that?
And I said, the President's Association for Student Finance.
He said, you've got to be kidding.
Apparently, from what I heard, goes up into the press box and asked Les about it.
And Les was still bragging about it.
I mean, he told everybody.
He said, watch this.
Watch what's fixing to happen.
He goes in there, and Dean Hannigan does some kind of deal, said, did you see the armadillo?
Wasn't that just the best BS you have ever seen in your whole life?
And Dean said, yes, sir, it certainly was.
And so Dean comes up and said, this didn't even happen, did it, Sharp?
I said, no, sir, I didn't see nothing.
No, that was good.
No, that's a good one.
And it did not make a single paper in the state.
How they did that, I don't know, but it was good.
It would make a few newspapers in the world today.
Oh, my God.
Isn't that the truth?
I mean, I bought every paper I could thinking, oh, Lord, we're in trouble.
All right.
Back to the, let's see, one last tradition that I had not mentioned is muster.
Do you remember when you first went to a muster?
Yep, I do.
Back then it was being held on the front of the systems building out here.
It's where we had the muster.
And I can't remember who the muster speaker was.
The most memorable muster speaker was, we had...
Max Cleland, when he had just returned from Vietnam, and now a U.S.
Senator, but he had just returned from Vietnam and had his legs.
I think he was one of the speakers.
But the most memorable muster was the one after Rutter died, when they called his name and the entire student body, 10,000 people, whatever it was, answered here for him.
But I think my junior year was moved into G. Raleigh.
And that was the year I was in charge.
The student life chairman had to put on the muster and that's where we're from.
And do you think muster is an important tradition at A&M?
Oh yeah.
I think all those traditions, particularly muster is.
What is the central factor of all of those?
Of all the traditions?
Bonding with each other.
Every one of them have to do with
You're not just another person in the world that we don't care anything about.
You're an Aggie.

We, even if I never met you, we went through things together that were similar and there's a reason that if I have any kind of way to show preference toward you, I'm going to do it over somebody else and not be shameful about it.
What creates Aggie spirit?
No.
What is Aggie Spirit?
Boy, I'd like to find a person that can define that.

I'm not sure you can put a definition of it, but from my perspective as I went through this institution and granted leaning heavily on experiences in the core, I think a big part of what creates Aggie Spirit is folks that go through the same trials together.
and learned that I think Aggie spirit is just the opposite of individualism.
Instead of being caught up in yourself, you're caught up in a family, a whole big family.
And I think, and it's not, I mean, it's not just a myth that people, that once you get out, you forget about it because I've seen it.
I've given it and I've received it.
I mean, I know there are people

People that would call me from when I first ran for controller and didn't run against, it's a different deal when you run against, you know, two Aggies that run against each other, but when, you know, when I first ran for controller or railroad commissioner, I mean, I get people call me up, call me up that was a chairman of the Republican Party in one county and said,
I'll resign if you want me to, or I can just work for you behind the scenes, or whatever you need.
It's a bond stronger than anything else you can find short of religion.
Might almost be.
Were you aware this was developing within you when you were an undergraduate?
When did you begin to feel this?
I don't know.

I'm sure we all noticed it was happening when we were there just because we were good friends but keep in mind most of us that I ran around with were people who outside our universe of a couple hundred kids in high school didn't know anybody else so this was our first thrust out into the world we didn't know if this was usual or unusual and stuff like that until we kind of got out into the world and found out that there's nothing
nothing like this deal.
But yeah, I think you experience the first time two or three of you are dressed down or humiliated or have to go through some common obstacle together is when it first starts bonding.
And I guess maybe it grows a little more when you get out and you find out that nobody else has been through this but you.
I'm not even sure Aggie jokes aren't helpful.
It brings people... Do you and your close friends think it's okay for Aggies to tell Aggie jokes when they're only Aggies in the room?
When they're only Aggies?
Yeah, most of them I'd say when they're only Aggies, but if it's somebody who starts telling them...
I mean, you could have ten Aggies in the room and they might tell one or two or something, but if
Some other guy says, well, I want to join in, and then nobody laughs at that.
That's what I've told people, that it's okay for an Aggie to tell an Aggie joke if it's within an Aggie setting, but no outsider.
But sometimes that doesn't fly too well.
Yeah, nobody likes outsiders.
I mean, I don't allow my family to tell Aggie jokes.
Now, what propelled you into leadership?
and on the campus?
Poor, one way or the other.
Okay.
I mean, it was, I mean, I, I, people always ask you, said, God, why'd you get into politics?
All this stuff you have to go through and all this stuff people say about you and dig up, you know, and all this kind of stuff.
And my response to that, after thinking about it a long time, is that
I have never had any opponent for a political office be to me as mean and nasty as the weakest sophomore in my outfit was.
I think I learned during that time to filter what's important and what's not, and so you get some bozo running against you that's screaming and hollering about this or that.
You're not even in the same league with the people that were screaming at me every morning for a year or two.
It kind of toughens you a little.
Early on, did you dream of running for student body president or corps commander or what?
No, I probably didn't start thinking about that until my sophomore year when I was elected sophomore class president.
And... And...
I would say shortly after that, though, I thought there was an opportunity to be.
All right.
Why a student body president instead of a corps commander?
If you'd had a choice, I presume you picked, you sought the one you wanted more?
I don't know.
I think it's two different sets of skills.
I mean, you can, political skills, getting along with people and stuff like that,
you know, work fine and getting things done.
Things don't happen in the Corps and the military through compromise.
Describe how you went about organizing to get ready to run for student body president.
Describe how you organized it and your campaign and so forth.
Well, there were, there were, I have, I've said on numerous occasions that politics at A&M
is much more difficult and much more intertwined than anything you'll experience in Texas.

I mean in Texas you've got South Texas that's much different from East Texas and Dallas and Houston that are different and San Antonio is different and the Panhandle is different and stuff like that but at A&M you had the Corps and if you had the Corps and they were happy that's a pretty serious block vote so you had to be number one in their eyes
And if you did that back then, you were well on your way.
But you also had the dormitories that worked on the bonfire.
And then you had folks that didn't work on the bonfire that were kind of kickers, you know, the country folks and folks like that.
You had the jocks that didn't pay much attention to anything outside of Caulfield or G. Riley White.
You had folks that lived off campus.
And then you had folks who lived off campus that were married that never came on the campus except to take courses and stuff like that.
And you had folks that were for the bonfire.
You had some folks, believe it or not, even back then, that were against it.
And so you had to figure out ways
do that stuff.
We organized, actually it was kind of between mine and Caperton's administration.
Kent was right before me.
We put like, I don't know if they still have refrigerators in the room, but the student government used to own those refrigerators and rent them to the student.
The bus system that was first put in was put in my senior year.
We proved that.
I forget, some outfit out of Austin, Enterprise Transportation or something like that, where the buses that now run
kind of stem from all that stuff.
As you're getting ready to organize your campaign to run for, who did you have, what kind of supporting organization did you try to create?
I would go, I went to those, all those clubs that I was a member of because I didn't want to eat in Duncan Dining Hall.
Back to those groups.
But the Corps then, I mean if you, the Corps didn't split its votes.
And my guess is they probably don't now, but I don't know.
And who were your primary opponents?
Well, Roger Miller.
And he was a civilian student?
He was vice president of the student body.
He was Kent's roommate.
And so he should have been heir to the civilian side of campus, which theoretically had a lot more votes.
But I was able to go into the civilian side because I was in those clubs or because of,
his position on Bonfire or whatever, in order to take some of those off, and he would, he could never have been successful in taking any significant number of core votes away from me.
Alright, so there were only two of you.
Did you have a slate of some of the candidates?
Not that year.
The year before we had that deal with Kent started.
And did the core, was there any kind of action the core leadership took to endorse you?
You mean like a primary?
Or a resolution, or did they pass the word?
Ah, yeah.

Well, there were rumors, of course, that the Corps held a primary, that the Yale leaders would go to each dorm and poll the seniors, or soon-to-be seniors, and say, okay, you've got a couple of guys in the Corps that want to run.
One is David Moore, who's on Corps staff, and the other one is this guy named Sharp who did.
And the rumors were that you would go to those guys and say, we can't have two from the Corps.
Which one would y'all do?
And the L.A.ers would tabulate that.
Sure rumor, of course.
During the campaign, about how long did it last?
Oh, three months.
Three, four months.
So there were posters and placards.
Yeah, posters and placards.
Ads in the back.
Oh no, it cost money.
Slipped flyers under the doors.
Rallies, we'd go to one side of campus and speak, the other side of campus and speak.
Were there any, there were no presidential debates.
We'd do it at the battalion.
They'd go to the battalion and they'd ask us questions or maybe a panel of folks ask us questions.
Nothing on the radio?
No.
Okay.
There was a limit to what we could spend.
I think it was like $2,000 or something like that.
But there were no MSC ballroom open big sessions where the two of you made speeches to the same crowd?
One, but it wasn't at the MSC.
It was in front of Walton Hall.
They had a big trailer out there.
Anybody wanted to run would come out and talk to whoever showed up to listen.
Which usually wasn't too many listening.
Did you have any kind of pre-election information about how you were doing?
Yeah, I knew when Roger said he was willing to consider alternatives to Bonfire that I was doing pretty well.
